{{Top|real|italics=1}}
'''''Sesame Street''''' is an educational television program designed for preschoolers, and is recognized as a pioneer of the contemporary standard which combines education and entertainment in children's television shows. Sesame Street also provided the first daily, national television showcase for [[W:c:muppet:Jim Henson|Jim Henson's]] Muppets. More than 4100 episodes of the show have been produced in 54 seasons, making it one of the longest-running shows in television history.

In two [[1980]] episodes, [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]] and [[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]] landed on the street in a [[Starship/Legends|spacecraft]], to deliver a [[Hologram/Legends|holographic]] message to [[W:c:muppet:Oscar the Grouch|Oscar the Grouch]] ([[W:c:muppet:Episode 1364|episode 1364]]) from [[Lothar the Grouch]] from the seventh moon of [[Zircon]], and another one to go to the park ([[W:c:muppet:Episode 1396|episode 1396]]).

Star Wars is also parodied/tributed in a ''Crumby Pictures'' parody sketch called ''Star S'mores''.

==Behind the scenes==
During [[Anthony Daniels]]' event at [[Celebration IV]], he showed some clips of his career as [[C-3PO/Legends|C-3PO]]&mdash;ranging from his ''Sesame Street'' episodes and ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' episode, to a C-3POs cereal commercial and ''[[The Star Wars Holiday Special]]''. Daniels gave insight into these appearances, and told some stories of his experiences working on them.

A segment filmed for repeat appearances outside of the aforementioned episodes, was released on the 2009 DVD [[W:c:muppet:Sesame Street: 40 Years of Sunny Days|''Sesame Street: 40 Years of Sunny Days'']].

==Connections==
[[Frank Oz]], performer of [[Yoda]], was the performer of ''Sesame Street'' Muppets [[W:c:muppet:Cookie Monster|Cookie Monster]], [[W:c:muppet:Grover|Grover]] and [[W:c:muppet:Bert|Bert]], and one of Jim Henson's closest collaborators.

